{
  "action_id": "850",
  "action_title": "Retain buffer zones around core habitat",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nOne before-and-after study in Australia found that grassland restoration that included leaving unmown buffers around ponds increased numbers of frog species.\nOne replicated, site comparison study in the USA found that retaining buffers along ridge tops within harvested forest increased Red Hills salamander abundance, body condition and genetic diversity. One replicated, controlled study in the USA found that retaining unmown buffers around ponds had mixed effects on tadpole survival and mass depending on species and site.\nOne replicated study in the USA\u00a0found that 30 m buffer zones around wetlands were not sufficient to protect marbled salamanders."
}

{
  "action_id": "309",
  "action_title": "Use signs and access restrictions to reduce disturbance at nest sites",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nSix studies (two replicated and controlled, two before-and-after and two small studies) from across the world found increased numbers of breeders, higher reproductive success or lower levels of disturbance in waders and terns following the start of access restrictions or the erection of signs near nesting areas. One Canadian study involved the use of multiple interventions.\nA before-and-after study from the USA found that a colony of black-crowned night herons Nycticorax nycticorax was successfully relocated to an area with no public access.\nOne small study from Europe and one replicated and controlled study from Antarctica found no effect of access restrictions on the reproductive success of eagles or penguins, respectively."
}

{
  "action_id": "2339",
  "action_title": "Use voluntary agreements with locals to reduce disturbance",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nWe found no studies that evaluated the effects on mammals of using voluntary agreements with locals to reduce disturbance.\n\n\u2018We found no studies\u2019 means that we have not yet found any studies that have directly evaluated this intervention during our systematic journal and report searches. Therefore, we have no evidence to indicate whether or not the intervention has any desirable or harmful effects."
}

